  "narrative": "Aric stands in the center of the cramped inn room, hand still resting on the pommel of his sword. The morning light casts pale rectangles across the worn wooden floor.\n\n\"Ah,\" he murmurs to himself, a slight smile crossing his weathered face. \"So this is Brindol.\"\n\nThe sounds of the waking town drift up through the grimy window—the cheerful chaos of the market below, the distant clang of a blacksmith's hammer, the whinny of horses from the livery. The room smells faintly of old wood and stale ale.\n\nA knock sounds at the door—not the innkeeper's friendly rap, but a sharper, more insistent rapping. A voice follows: \"Sir? Checking out this morning? The missus says breakfast is ready whenever you are.\"\n\nThe flyer about goblins still waits by the table leg, its corners curling with age.",
